I pneumocytes","Endothelial cells separated by elastic tissue"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EType I pneumocytes and endothelial cells separated by basement membrane\u003C/strong\u003E accurately describes the three-layered structure of the alveolar-capillary membrane (also called the blood-gas barrier). This structure is optimised for efficient gas exchange through its minimal thickness (approximately 0.5 micrometres) while maintaining structural integrity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType II pneumocytes and endothelial cells only\u003C/strong\u003E omits the essential basement membrane and incorrectly identifies the epithelial cell type (Type II cells primarily produce surfactant)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esingle layer of squamous epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient for maintaining separation between air and blood compartments\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Edouble layer of type I pneumocytes\u003C/strong\u003E fails to account for the endothelial component and basement membrane\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndothelial cells separated by elastic tissue\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly describes the membrane structure and would create an excessive diffusion barrier\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis three-layered structure allows for efficient gas exchange via passive diffusion while maintaining the separation between air and blood compartments.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The alveolar-capillary membrane consists of three layers: alveolar epithelium, basement membrane, and capillary endothelium.","Gas exchange occurs via passive diffusion across the alveolar-capillary membrane.","The total thickness of the alveolar-capillary membrane is approximately 0.5 micrometres."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64025"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17815"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64025"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T08:27:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T08:28:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10529"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78682"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"htt